  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]},{"name":"Phillip","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Camille, Esme, Gaston, Monique.","English (mainly Yorkshire), Scottish, and German: variant of   Philip  .","Americanized form of French   Philippe  , Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian or Croatian   Filip  . Compare   Philip  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McPhillips","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Fitzgerald.","Scottish and Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Philib</b>, a patronymic from a Gaelic form of the personal name   Phillip  , with excrescent English <i>-s</i>. See also   McKillip  ."]},{"name":"Piela","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Casimir, Janina, Jerzy, Tadeuz.","Polish:","from a local vernacular derivative of the personal name<i>Filip</i> (see   Phillip  )."]},{"name":"Philip","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Varughese, Mathai, Babu, Reji, Anil, Binu, Neena, Prema, Raju, Reena, Susheela, Aleykutty.","Scottish, English, German, Dutch, and Jewish: from the Greek personal name <i>Philippos</i> (from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’). In the New Testament this name is borne by one of the apostles; it was also borne by various other early Christian saints. It owes part of its popularity to the medieval romances about Alexander the Great, whose father was Philip of Macedon. As a Jewish name, it represents a borrowing of the personal name from Christians. As a Highland Scottish surname, it represents an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhilib</b> ‘son of Philip’. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Spanish   Felipe  , Catalan <b>Felip</b>, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian or Croatian   Filip  , Albanian   Filipi  , and their derivatives (see examples at   Philips  ). The name <i>Philip</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Philipose   and   Pothen  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Phillip  .","French (southern) and Breton (Finistère): variant of   Philippe  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gwenvyr verch Phillip was born as the daughter of Phillip ap Griffith ap Meredith. She had at least 3 sons with Einion ap Llywelyn of Llwyn Melyn."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1224–1316":"1224–1316","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1316":"1316","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","about 1235":"umbes 1235","Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales.":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1224–1316":"1224–1316","1235–Male":"1235–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1316":"1316","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","about 1235":"noin 1235","Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales.":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","1224–1316":"1224–1316","1235–Male":"1235–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1316":"1316","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","about 1235":"environ 1235","Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales.":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Gwenvyr verch Phillip est née, fille de Phillip ap Griffith ap Meredith. Elle a eu au moins 3 fils avec Einion ap Llywelyn of Llwyn Melyn."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1224–1316":"1224–1316","1235–Male":"1235–Verstorben","–Male":"Verstorben","1316":"1316","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","about 1235":"um 1235","Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales.":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales","lifeSummary":"Gwenvyr verch Phillip wurde, als Tochter von Phillip ap Griffith ap Meredith geboren. Sie hatte mit Einion ap Llywelyn of Llwyn Melyn mindestens 3 Söhne."},"ht":{"–":"Desede","–Female":"Desede","1224–1316":"1224–1316","1235–Male":"1235–Desede","–Male":"De